## Project 4: Real-World Pharmaceutical SDF Analysis

### Task Objective
- Applied the complete OCR pipeline to a real scanned pharmaceutical Supporting Documentation File (SDF).
- Extracted important document information including:
  - Vendor/Manufacturer name
  - Product name and product code
  - Lot/Batch numbers
  - Dates
  - Document type
  - Signature information
  - Document reference numbers

### Full OCR Processing Workflow
1. Loaded scanned pharmaceutical PDF into the OCR pipeline.
2. Applied image preprocessing to improve document quality.
3. Used Tesseract OCR to extract text from the scanned document.
4. Cleaned OCR output and corrected recognition errors.
5. Used regex patterns to locate important pharmaceutical fields.
6. Used bounding boxes to identify the location of extracted information.
7. Converted extracted fields into structured JSON format for AI processing.

## Pharmaceutical SDF Field Extraction
- Built regex-based extraction logic to identify key fields:
  - Vendor/Manufacturer
  - Product Name
  - Product Code
  - Lot Number
  - Document Type
  - Signature Date
  - Signatory Name
  - Document Reference Number

### Why Structured Extraction is Important
- Raw OCR text does not preserve document structure.
- Structured extraction allows AI systems to understand relationships between fields.
- Enables automated document review and data processing.

## Challenges During Real-World OCR Extraction
- The biggest challenge was handling document layout and formatting.
- Although the document was readable by humans, OCR struggled with:
  - Correct ordering of text sections.
  - Connecting labels with their corresponding values.
  - Extracting information from signatures and reference fields.
  - Maintaining relationships between dates and document sections.
- Additional cleaning, regex extraction, and bounding box localization were needed to create structured output.

